in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705193,"age":2,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705195,"age":47,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Agnes Caldecote was born in 1335, in Caldecote, Cheshire, England. She married Ralph de Wilbraham in 1361, in Caldecote, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 4 sons."},"et":{"1335–":"1335–Surnud","1340–1388":"1340–1388","1364–Male":"1364–Surnud","1366–1406":"1366–1406","1370–Male":"1370–Surnud","1372–1420":"1372–1420","1335–Female":"1335–Surnud","about 1370":"umbes 1370","1340":"1340","1361":"1361","1372":"1372","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","1337":"1337","1335":"1335","1366":"1366","1388":"1388","1453":"1453","1420":"1420","1364":"1364","about 1366":"umbes 1366","about 1364":"umbes 1364","1406":"1406","Carden, Cheshire, England":"Carden, Cheshire, England","Caldecote, Cheshire, England":"Caldecote, 